1
00:00:01,810 --> 00:00:04,610
Episode 3

2
00:00:13,600 --> 00:00:20,900
Timing and Subtitles by the Sing To Me Team @ viki

3
00:00:34,690 --> 00:00:37,800
Mr. Tone Deaf

4
00:00:42,610 --> 00:00:44,630
Hello?

5
00:00:46,190 --> 00:00:48,930
- Did you sleep well?
- Yes, thanks to you.

6
00:00:48,930 --> 00:00:53,140
I can't say, did I fall asleep less than five minutes after you called?

7
00:00:53,140 --> 00:00:55,400
What a relief.

8
00:00:55,400 --> 00:00:59,130
Then...what should we do? Shall we start from today?

9
00:00:59,130 --> 00:01:00,850
Yes, of course. Let's do it.

10
00:01:00,850 --> 00:01:05,440
- There are conditions.
- Conditions? What are they?

11
00:01:05,440 --> 00:01:08,910
The part-time fee is 10,000 won (about $8) per day, paid in advance, a week at a time.

12
00:01:08,910 --> 00:01:10,890
In the event of termination, we will come to a mutual agreement ...

13
00:01:10,890 --> 00:01:15,890
But, on termination, I won't return the money already received. Is that alright with  you?

14
00:01:15,890 --> 00:01:19,200
We will come to a mutual agreement on termination?

15
00:01:19,200 --> 00:01:22,910
Well, if that's what you want, then let's do it, I guess.

16
00:01:22,910 --> 00:01:25,210
Don't worry. I won't disappear after pocketing the money.

17
00:01:25,210 --> 00:01:29,170
Then, tonight at 11:50 p.m.

18
00:01:31,530 --> 00:01:34,000
I feel like somehow I got the short end of the stick.

19
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:37,410
Even so, who else could put me to sleep so peacefully?

20
00:01:40,490 --> 00:01:45,270
Practice is a battle. A one-woman battle!

21
00:01:48,800 --> 00:01:51,120
Uncle

22
00:01:54,360 --> 00:01:56,510
Hello.

23
00:01:57,280 --> 00:02:01,890
Grab the bouquet more tightly. Okay.

24
00:02:01,890 --> 00:02:05,670
You pose so well. Okay, okay.

25
00:02:05,670 --> 00:02:10,560
Anyway, the two of you are the same. Both Su Yeong and you.

26
00:02:10,560 --> 00:02:13,660
You never call first. You brats.

27
00:02:13,660 --> 00:02:19,440
Stop nagging her when she’s modeling for free. We should be thankful she’s even here, right?

28
00:02:19,440 --> 00:02:25,110
Don’t be ridiculous. We raised and fed them. Should I make them pay me for that?

29
00:02:25,110 --> 00:02:27,910
Okay, good job.

30
00:02:30,960 --> 00:02:36,920
You’re upset again, aren’t you? Alright, I’ll come by more often.

31
00:02:36,920 --> 00:02:39,650
You brat, you're a good talker.

32
00:02:53,280 --> 00:02:56,930
Look at how shabby we look.

33
00:03:08,800 --> 00:03:12,670
I lived in a big house.

34
00:03:12,670 --> 00:03:18,870
My biological parents passed away when I was five.

35
00:03:18,870 --> 00:03:23,290
Yi Yeong, the sujebi is getting soggy. Eat it before it gets soggier.

36
00:03:23,290 --> 00:03:26,130
Yes, I'm coming!
(sujebi: soup made of dough flakes torn by hand, with vegetables)

37
00:03:38,050 --> 00:03:42,040
It's delicious.

38
00:03:44,260 --> 00:03:50,250
Look at her. Even if she’s off duty, how could a doctor sleep in until the afternoon? Geez.

39
00:03:50,250 --> 00:03:53,550
Don't fall asleep at the dining table. Sleep.
Episode 3

40
00:03:53,550 --> 00:03:59,250
That hurts. Can’t a doctor sleep in? Doctors are also human beings, right?

41
00:03:59,250 --> 00:04:03,060
We worked so hard to educate you, yet you always talk back.

42
00:04:03,060 --> 00:04:06,970
Ah, right. Su Yeong, make sure you’re free this weekend.

43
00:04:06,970 --> 00:04:11,770
If you don’t show up this time either, I’ll remove you from our family register.

44
00:04:12,510 --> 00:04:14,790
- Is it another blind date?
- I think so.

45
00:04:14,790 --> 00:04:18,630
What’s the use? She’s failed at every blind date.

46
00:04:18,630 --> 00:04:21,570
It’s because I took after you.

47
00:04:21,570 --> 00:04:25,130
Look at you.

48
00:04:26,730 --> 00:04:31,560
That hurts!

49
00:04:40,360 --> 00:04:46,360
I became a percussionist thanks to my uncle.

50
00:04:59,240 --> 00:05:06,360
When I was in elementary school, he took me to the marine rescue parade.

51
00:05:07,050 --> 00:05:12,770
Those drums captivated me.

52
00:05:14,960 --> 00:05:20,290
Why I did I choose these drums and not the piano or violin, you may ask?

53
00:05:26,780 --> 00:05:30,620
I enjoyed the sound they made.

54
00:05:30,620 --> 00:05:34,670
But it’s probably because of my uncle’s hands.

55
00:05:34,670 --> 00:05:40,780
They were similar to my dad’s. They were big and warm.

56
00:05:49,080 --> 00:05:54,670
For my dear uncle, I’ll practice until the end.

57
00:06:02,840 --> 00:06:07,680
President Go Min Jung

58
00:06:07,680 --> 00:06:11,530
The Sinyeong Philharmonic Orchestra 20th Anniversary Concert

59
00:06:11,530 --> 00:06:17,930
Isn’t the poster too flashy? You should’ve just kept to the usual design. The orchestra supporters’ association will hate this.

60
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:24,500
The audience prefers things that are different these days. I’ll persuade the Chairwoman.

61
00:06:26,090 --> 00:06:31,570
- What’s with the theme item? Weren’t we going with Tchaikovsky?
- He chose Mahler’s Symphony No. 2.

62
00:06:31,570 --> 00:06:36,570
Who? Nam Ju Wan? Doesn’t the Chairwoman  get a say in this?

63
00:06:36,570 --> 00:06:39,990
We agreed to do Ars Nova*  for a season. The fans are anticipating it.
(*15th cent. music. But in Korea = "post-romantic and modern")

64
00:06:39,990 --> 00:06:44,920
We agreed to do Mahler’s music next year. We don’t have enough budget for this.

65
00:06:44,920 --> 00:06:50,290
You know the Chairwoman's  preference better than I do. Are you trying to get me into trouble, or what?

66
00:06:50,290 --> 00:06:55,500
Reprint the poster, talk with Maestro Nam, and change the main composition.

67
00:06:55,500 --> 00:06:58,850
All he knows is the Supporters’ Association and its Chairwoman, the Chairwoman!

68
00:06:58,850 --> 00:07:02,070
He might as well lick her feet.

69
00:07:02,070 --> 00:07:07,190
He doesn’t dare to speak up once about sponsorship.

70
00:07:07,190 --> 00:07:11,440
- Maestro Nam is in his office, right?
- What? About that...

71
00:07:16,280 --> 00:07:21,650
I was about to tell you that he just left.

72
00:07:21,650 --> 00:07:27,830
I have so many things to discuss with him. Where did he go?

73
00:07:28,500 --> 00:07:35,610
How could you still not know his whereabouts? Find him this instant and let me know.

74
00:07:37,700 --> 00:07:39,680
What are you doing?

75
00:07:40,800 --> 00:07:42,890
Go!

76
00:08:03,670 --> 00:08:06,510
Yang Su Jeong

77
00:08:10,960 --> 00:08:15,690
Isn’t this yours? You left it behind.

78
00:08:15,690 --> 00:08:18,070
- It was intentional.
-  What?

79
00:08:18,070 --> 00:08:23,910
I was getting too many calls. Anyway, thank you.

80
00:08:23,910 --> 00:08:27,440
Hey, wait!

81
00:08:27,440 --> 00:08:35,670
About this phone... my name’s not on it and I remember leaving it in the restroom.

82
00:08:37,160 --> 00:08:42,290
I saw your performance when you were at the Asia Philharmonic. And that ringtone is Bach’s “Unaccompanied Cello Suites”.

83
00:08:42,290 --> 00:08:47,590
Among our dinner guests tonight, I could only think of one person who would use that.

84
00:08:48,300 --> 00:08:50,730
I’ll go now.

85
00:09:19,160 --> 00:09:21,990
That looks so good...

86
00:09:24,870 --> 00:09:27,890
I'm hungry.

87
00:09:32,520 --> 00:09:35,400
-  Are they eating beef?
- You scared me!

88
00:09:36,350 --> 00:09:42,720
When you come close to someone, please give some sign.

89
00:09:45,910 --> 00:09:51,420
You're always standing there. If I want to see you, I just need to go outside of the beef restaurant.

90
00:09:51,420 --> 00:09:55,230
No.  What are you saying that I do outside the beef restaurant?

91
00:09:55,230 --> 00:09:59,660
You ate all the meat by yourself.  I didn't get a single bite.

92
00:09:59,660 --> 00:10:04,570
Are you the only one with a mouth? I also have a mouth!

93
00:10:06,870 --> 00:10:10,720
Don't you know how to stop minding other people's business? Let's go.

94
00:10:11,990 --> 00:10:16,680
Hold on. How do you know my name?

95
00:10:18,830 --> 00:10:24,730
You wrote it there. You used the giant magic marker.

96
00:10:25,560 --> 00:10:29,720
- You aren't even in grade school.
- Stop looking.

97
00:10:29,720 --> 00:10:34,180
By the way, why did you suddenly start speaking informally to me? Listening to you doesn't sit right with me...

98
00:10:34,180 --> 00:10:38,060
- You started speaking informally first, don't you remember?
- Me, when? (formally, then informally)

99
00:10:38,060 --> 00:10:40,420
Where do you think you're going?
(Informally, without the "yo" ending)

100
00:10:42,490 --> 00:10:46,780
Don't go! This is the way to my house, don't go!

101
00:10:48,920 --> 00:10:50,650
What else did you say? That...

102
00:10:50,650 --> 00:10:55,810
Sleep with me, okay?
Let's sleep together, already!

103
00:10:57,870 --> 00:11:05,010
Stop. I get it. I got it, so end it right there.

104
00:11:10,010 --> 00:11:12,520
- What are you going to do now?
- Why are you asking?

105
00:11:12,520 --> 00:11:16,870
If it's not a big deal, I thought we could hang out together.

106
00:11:16,870 --> 00:11:21,840
Why would I hang out with you.  I don't hang out with strangers.

107
00:11:21,840 --> 00:11:24,820
But you would sleep with a stranger...

108
00:11:24,820 --> 00:11:28,300
You are really too much.  Are you going to keep on doing that?

109
00:11:28,300 --> 00:11:36,200
I have trouble falling asleep. I just wanted someone who could help me sleep. That's all that I meant.

110
00:11:36,200 --> 00:11:40,800
- Get out of the way.
- You can't just brush me aside and go.

111
00:11:40,800 --> 00:11:45,050
- Give me my part-time fee.
- What did you say?

112
00:11:45,050 --> 00:11:50,450
You have a  bad memory. I told you. Part-time fee.

113
00:11:50,450 --> 00:11:54,680
Paid once a week, in advance.

114
00:11:59,910 --> 00:12:01,900
Jeez.

115
00:12:06,020 --> 00:12:11,850
I don't have enough.  I'll give you the rest next time. Satisfied?

116
00:12:13,010 --> 00:12:18,300
What a shame.  I was thinking of having some beef with my part-time pay.

117
00:12:22,890 --> 00:12:26,020
This guy really tries to see how far he can go.  Is making fun of people your hobby?

118
00:12:26,020 --> 00:12:32,070
Well, think however you want, but "I'm starving" is written all over your face.  It's betraying you.

119
00:12:32,070 --> 00:12:35,070
Your friends said he's in this neighborhood, so we are going to meet.  Let's go.

120
00:12:35,070 --> 00:12:41,860
Aren't you letting me go? I'm not going to eat with you. Do you think I would eat meat you bought?

121
00:12:51,160 --> 00:12:55,260
- I heard you say you wouldn't eat meat I bought...
- Stop laughing.

122
00:12:55,260 --> 00:12:57,750
After eating, you won't say we're going Dutch, right?

123
00:12:57,750 --> 00:13:02,390
- Do I look like that kind of person?
- I know people from their appearance.

124
00:13:02,390 --> 00:13:07,560
-  But it's kind of strange.  We've known each other only a few days and we are grilling meat together.

125
00:13:07,560 --> 00:13:12,310
From seeing your mallet, it seems you play percussion instruments. Are you an orchestra member somewhere?

126
00:13:12,310 --> 00:13:15,530
Of course. I'm a member of the Sinyeong Philharmonic.

127
00:13:15,530 --> 00:13:21,400
It would be nice if I could say that, but I'm still unemployed.

128
00:13:21,400 --> 00:13:26,510
Every time I went to an audition, I failed. Seventeen times in three years.

129
00:13:26,510 --> 00:13:29,700
The audition for the Sinyeong Philharmonic, a few days ago, was a total disaster.

130
00:13:29,700 --> 00:13:37,160
Well, seventeen times in three years is not that bad.
Nowadays, people submit their resumés a hundred times.

131
00:13:37,160 --> 00:13:44,240
Right. I think so too. For a dream, it's not bad.

132
00:13:45,920 --> 00:13:53,640
But then, I'm trying to do well, but that doesn't work out. It's worse than I thought.

133
00:13:54,690 --> 00:13:57,970
Because I am so nervous, I fail at every audition.

134
00:13:57,970 --> 00:14:02,700
If I were less nervous, I wouldn't make ridiculous mistakes, right?

135
00:14:09,600 --> 00:14:15,540
I know a way to relax... Shall I tell you?

136
00:14:15,540 --> 00:14:19,860
I've tried everything on the internet.  They have all been useless.

137
00:14:19,860 --> 00:14:23,880
It's a method I was personally taught by a pianist who moved to England.

138
00:14:23,880 --> 00:14:31,500
It's a secret of the Chinese imperial family from the time of the first Qin emperor.

139
00:14:33,250 --> 00:14:36,030
- The first Qin emperor?
- Yeah.

140
00:14:42,480 --> 00:14:46,970
Write the Chinese character for person three times in a row like this.

141
00:14:52,080 --> 00:14:55,980
- This it it?
- It works 100%.

142
00:14:55,980 --> 00:14:59,900
- Really?
- Of course.

143
00:15:07,050 --> 00:15:09,770
Inhale one more time.

144
00:15:10,760 --> 00:15:13,740
How is it?

145
00:15:19,110 --> 00:15:21,840
Of course it's a lie.  Did you believe it?

146
00:15:23,190 --> 00:15:29,470
Now I see this guy is just plain bad.  You make fun of people non-stop.

147
00:15:30,570 --> 00:15:33,430
What? You're leaving?

148
00:15:33,430 --> 00:15:36,790
Since I'm full, I should go.

149
00:15:38,270 --> 00:15:46,320
Don't forget to call me later. Don't just pocket the part-time pay which is like gold. You know, right?

150
00:15:46,320 --> 00:15:50,930
I will follow you to the end of the earth to get it back.

151
00:15:52,470 --> 00:15:54,840
I'm leaving.

152
00:16:05,090 --> 00:16:09,840
Candle? Okay. Humidifier? Okay. Curtain? Okay.

153
00:16:17,950 --> 00:16:20,260
It's come.

154
00:16:26,390 --> 00:16:31,800
Hello. Really, it's like a knife cutting time.  Did you know you are off by less than a second?

155
00:16:31,800 --> 00:16:35,770
Of course it is. I got paid in advance.

156
00:16:35,770 --> 00:16:37,170
What's the song for today?

157
00:16:37,170 --> 00:16:42,700
I'll do whatever song you request.  If if you don't have any, I'll sing what I feel like singing.

158
00:16:42,700 --> 00:16:46,420
Then sing whatever you want, please.

159
00:16:46,420 --> 00:16:49,130
Then, for tonight...

160
00:16:51,080 --> 00:16:54,030
"This song", by 2AM*.
(K-pop boy group)

161
00:16:54,030 --> 00:16:56,570
Give me a second.

162
00:17:00,150 --> 00:17:02,770
Do it now.

163
00:17:08,220 --> 00:17:14,630
♫ Although I'd love  to buy you a pretty necklace.

164
00:17:14,630 --> 00:17:20,400
♫ Although I'd love to give you a nice ride

165
00:17:20,400 --> 00:17:25,480
♫ Although I'd liove to dress you in pretty clothes

166
00:17:25,480 --> 00:17:31,500
♫ Although I'd love to take you to someplace nice

167
00:17:31,500 --> 00:17:34,590
It's truly phenomenal. A god-awful voice.

168
00:17:34,600 --> 00:17:42,500
♫ The hand placed in my pocket doesn't hold anything.

169
00:17:42,560 --> 00:17:50,260
♫ How can I hold onto you?

170
00:17:50,260 --> 00:17:55,410
What kind of person is he? His behaviour is a totally arrogant act.

171
00:17:55,410 --> 00:18:02,220
No way.  A member of the country's élite wouldn't take a part-time job for 70 thousand won a week.   Then, a bum?

172
00:18:02,220 --> 00:18:08,460
♫ I only have this song to give you ♫

173
00:18:08,460 --> 00:18:16,460
♫ The only thing I have is this voice

174
00:18:19,830 --> 00:18:25,500
♫ Although I don't know if this will make you smile

175
00:18:25,500 --> 00:18:28,390
♫ Even so I'll try to sing

176
00:18:28,390 --> 00:18:30,830
I have to sleep, so why am I doing this?

177
00:18:30,830 --> 00:18:37,700
♫ I will hope

178
00:18:39,210 --> 00:18:43,160
I am so curious about him.

179
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:49,940
Mr. Tone Deaf

180
00:19:48,060 --> 00:19:53,000
I Wanna Hear Your Song

181
00:20:23,840 --> 00:20:26,700
Why aren't you getting up?

182
00:20:27,990 --> 00:20:31,280
Three seconds to get up or I'm pulling the sheet off.

183
00:20:31,280 --> 00:20:34,590
I don't care about that at all.

184
00:20:34,590 --> 00:20:37,600
Give me a break!  Have you forgotten today's audition?

185
00:20:37,600 --> 00:20:39,860
Because you're stubborn, we still have open positions.

186
00:20:39,860 --> 00:20:44,360
Get dressed and come out. I'm going to take your picture and post it on the homepage.

187
00:20:47,190 --> 00:20:50,350
What's the matter?  You're a scary person.

188
00:20:54,110 --> 00:20:55,740
Maestro Nam will be ten minutes late.

189
00:20:55,740 --> 00:20:58,270
Please tell the applicants to be patient.

190
00:21:17,130 --> 00:21:19,670
Practice Room

191
00:22:30,970 --> 00:22:32,360
Maestro Nam.

192
00:22:32,360 --> 00:22:35,060
This is the audition...

193
00:22:46,760 --> 00:22:49,310
Now. Lift them up.

194
00:22:49,310 --> 00:22:51,260
Start.

195
00:22:51,260 --> 00:22:54,100
One Two One Two

196
00:22:54,100 --> 00:22:56,400
One Two

197
00:22:56,400 --> 00:22:59,500
Carry on. Continue.

198
00:23:01,340 --> 00:23:05,470
Yes. One Two

199
00:23:05,470 --> 00:23:08,410
Maestro Nam

200
00:23:12,440 --> 00:23:13,350
Hello?

201
00:23:13,350 --> 00:23:16,980
Hong Yi Yeong, what are you doing right now?

202
00:23:16,980 --> 00:23:19,430
I'm in the middle of a lesson.

203
00:23:19,430 --> 00:23:22,790
Really? Then call me when your lesson is over.

204
00:23:22,790 --> 00:23:24,850
Let's eat something sweet.

205
00:23:27,610 --> 00:23:29,620
Something sweet?

206
00:23:34,010 --> 00:23:39,750
I drank a lot yesterday and I've been craving something sweet since the morning.

207
00:23:39,750 --> 00:23:42,590
Don't I smell like alcohol?

208
00:23:42,590 --> 00:23:44,740
No, I don't think so.

209
00:23:44,740 --> 00:23:46,800
What kind of lesson was that?

210
00:23:47,820 --> 00:23:52,690
I teach kids three times a week.  It's not for an entrance exam.

211
00:23:52,690 --> 00:23:55,480
I see...

212
00:23:55,480 --> 00:23:59,960
By the way. I've decided on the opening piece for the inaugural concert.

213
00:23:59,960 --> 00:24:01,800
The opening piece for the inaugural concert?

214
00:24:01,800 --> 00:24:03,310
Yes.

215
00:24:03,310 --> 00:24:07,540
Berlioz's "Symphonie Fantastique".

216
00:24:08,620 --> 00:24:10,110
What?

217
00:24:10,110 --> 00:24:13,010
You know? Come to the rehearsal by 10 am. tomorrow.

218
00:24:13,010 --> 00:24:17,980
Be on your toes. Let's try to do well.

219
00:24:29,490 --> 00:24:33,390
Berlioz' Symphonie Fantastique.

220
00:24:33,390 --> 00:24:36,450
Timpani...

221
00:24:36,450 --> 00:24:39,460
The timpani are...

222
00:24:39,460 --> 00:24:41,200
Two large sets ...(Berlioz's use ot two  sets of timpani was thought to be radical in the 19th century)

223
00:24:43,440 --> 00:24:46,070
I passed!

224
00:24:46,070 --> 00:24:47,990
Oh my gosh!

225
00:24:49,970 --> 00:24:51,080
Hello?

226
00:24:51,080 --> 00:24:55,190
Unni.

227
00:24:55,190 --> 00:24:56,670
I said I passed my audition!

228
00:24:56,670 --> 00:24:58,790
The conductor wants me to come to the rehearsal starting tomorrow!

229
00:24:58,790 --> 00:25:02,360
I thought you were calling me about a blind date.

230
00:25:04,750 --> 00:25:08,260
Congratulations. I will treat you this weekend to ribeye steak.

231
00:25:08,260 --> 00:25:10,230
Okay, keep your promise!

232
00:25:10,230 --> 00:25:11,610
I'll call Aunt and Uncle.

233
00:25:11,610 --> 00:25:15,100
Okay! What do I do?

234
00:25:15,100 --> 00:25:18,510
I passed and she's treating me to tasty beef.

235
00:25:21,190 --> 00:25:24,270
How old are you?

236
00:25:24,270 --> 00:25:27,350
Twenty-seven.

237
00:25:28,660 --> 00:25:30,480
Then that's fine.

238
00:25:30,480 --> 00:25:32,820
Do you have a bit of time?

239
00:25:36,480 --> 00:25:40,030
The hardest thing in the world for me is to choose something like this.

240
00:25:40,030 --> 00:25:42,550
It's a little easier if you choose to match the age.

241
00:25:42,550 --> 00:25:44,980
What's the age of the recipient?

242
00:25:44,980 --> 00:25:46,320
Twenty-seven.

243
00:25:46,320 --> 00:25:48,420
If she's twenty-seven...

244
00:25:48,420 --> 00:25:50,010
Is he seeing someone my age?

245
00:25:50,010 --> 00:25:52,640
Which one do you like?

246
00:25:52,640 --> 00:25:54,390
Me?

247
00:25:56,120 --> 00:25:58,910
I... the left one?

248
00:25:58,910 --> 00:26:01,910
Then I'll take the right one.

249
00:26:03,550 --> 00:26:05,210
Of course.

250
00:26:06,020 --> 00:26:08,320
You choose one too.

251
00:26:08,320 --> 00:26:10,340
Me?

252
00:26:13,940 --> 00:26:15,540
You worked hard today.

253
00:26:15,540 --> 00:26:17,620
No, I really didn't. It wasn't hard work.

254
00:26:17,620 --> 00:26:20,270
Thank you for the gift!

255
00:26:20,270 --> 00:26:23,800
Don't say something like a farewell. It's awkward for me to say farewell.

256
00:26:25,530 --> 00:26:30,690
Can I ask you something, sir?

257
00:26:30,690 --> 00:26:32,120
Go for it.

258
00:26:32,120 --> 00:26:36,540
I was curious as to how I passed my audition.

259
00:26:36,540 --> 00:26:39,330
I made an incredible mistake.

260
00:26:40,520 --> 00:26:43,020
Because I needed you.

261
00:26:43,020 --> 00:26:44,660
Excuse me?

262
00:26:48,210 --> 00:26:50,460
I liked your performance that day.

263
00:26:50,460 --> 00:26:54,900
I liked that feeling of desperation.  You probably used to do that in college, too.

264
00:26:54,900 --> 00:26:56,740
Do well.

265
00:26:57,920 --> 00:26:59,780
Thank you.

266
00:27:03,810 --> 00:27:05,750
Thank you!
